IntroductionÂ¶

We are going to use the movielens 20M dataset for our analysis. The dataset is downloaded from https://grouplens.org/datasets/movielens/ . This dataset consists of 20 million ratings and 465,000 tag applications applied to 27,000 movies by 138,000 users. We are using tidyverse library for..... . The lubridate is used to do clean and convert the date in a proper format. Similarly stringr library is used to convert the genres separated by | to appear as separate entity.

ObjectivesÂ¶

The main objective of this project is to analyze the following three questions :

  1. Which genres receive the highest ratings? How does this change over time?
  2. Build model to predict ratings for future unseen data (test data).
  3. Which factor affects the popularity of movie? Is it the budget or the length of movie?

Let's convert the timestamp to date format

movie_genre$timestamp=as.Date(movie_genre$timestamp,format="%Y")
In [30]:
class(movie_genre$timestamp)
'Date'
In [32]:
movie_genre_lag = movie_genre %>%                     
                    group_by(genres) %>% 
                    arrange(timestamp) %>% 
                    mutate(lags = (lag(numeric_ratings)))  
# Replace NA with zero
movie_genre_lag[is.na(movie_genre_lag)] <- 0
In [33]:
#Find the average yearly change for each genre and calculate the avgChange using the lag function
movie_genre_change = movie_genre_lag %>% 
                    group_by(genres,timestamp) %>% 
                    summarize(avgChange = mean(lags))
In [86]:
# Plot the change in ratings per genre per year
movie_genre_change%>%  ggplot(aes(x=timestamp, y=avgChange, color = genres)) + 
                       geom_line(size = 0.6, alpha = 1) + 
                       theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=45,hjust=1))+
                       facet_wrap(~genres, ncol=2, scales='free_y')

Here, we create a function to reduce the data pollution by the movies having lower ranks. The function will generate the weighted average for ranking which is used on imdb website to rank their top 250 movies. This will provide the higher ranking to the movies with higher rating and reviews.

In [63]:
rating_weighted <- function(A, C, m, M) {
  return (C/(C+m))*A + (m/(C+m))*M
}

avg_rating <- movielens_tmdb_combined_results %>%
  mutate(weighted_rating = rating_weighted(vote_average, vote_count, 500, mean(vote_average))) %>%
  arrange(desc(weighted_rating))
